               <!--<desc type="site-data" xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000300-1">
               Kaiyuan Monastery (開元寺) is located in West Street of Licheng District in Quanzhou (泉州鯉城區西街). It is the largest Buddhist monastery in Fujian Province, and one of the major historical and cultural sites protected at the national level (全國重點文物保護單位). It was initially built in 685 or 686 during <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang dynasty</term> under the original name Lotus Monastery (蓮花寺). In the twenty-sixth year of Tang Kaiyuan (738), it was bestowed the name Kaiyuan Monastery. There are extant structures from the <term ref="/keyword/k000076">Southern Song</term> to <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing dynasty</term>. Along the central axis, behind the Hall of Four Heavenly Kings (天王殿) is the main Mahavira Hall (大雄寶殿), of which most scholars agree the extant buildings are relics of late <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming dynasty</term>. Behind the main hall is the Sweet Dew Altar of Precepts (甘露戒壇), used for Buddhist believers to ordain the precepts. The caisson (藻井) above the altar applies brackets made of 24 statues of Flying Apsaras holding musical instruments (飛天月伎). There are two stone pagodas in both sides of the axis. The east one named Zhenguo Pagoda (鎮國塔), was originally wooden pagoda in Tang dynasty, and was rebuilt in stone during 1238-1250. The west one named Renshou Pagoda (仁壽塔), was originally wooden pagoda in Wudai Dynasties, and was rebuilt during 1228-1237. Every storey of both pagodas is carved with reliefs with vivid human figures. 
               </desc>-->
